## Key Differences

### 1. Offline-First Architecture vs Cloud-Dependent Design

What sets Tero.Ops apart is its offline-first Progressive Web App architecture. Built on the full Workbox 6.6.x suite — including precaching, background sync, and broadcast update — Tero.Ops caches all operational data on-device and syncs automatically when connectivity returns. Field technicians on remote vessels can log job records, record meter readings, and attach inspection photos with zero internet access.

Unlike Maximo and similar enterprise CMMS platforms, Tero.Ops does not treat offline operation as an optional add-on. It is the default operating mode.

### 2. Four Maintenance Trigger Types vs Calendar-Only Scheduling

The key difference in maintenance scheduling is that Tero.Ops supports four job occurrence types in a single job definition: One-Off, Time-Based (calendar interval), Meter-Based (triggered when an engine hours or fuel threshold is crossed), and **Whichever Comes First** (the earliest of a time or meter condition).

Unlike eMaint and other traditional CMMS tools that schedule maintenance on fixed calendar intervals only, Tero.Ops is purpose-built for condition-based maintenance — ensuring work happens when equipment actually needs it, not on an arbitrary date.

### 3. Unified EAM Platform vs Siloed Modules

What sets Tero.Ops apart is that procurement, inventory, work orders, contractor projects, and asset management are all native to a single platform — not bolted-together integrations. An inventory request flows directly into a purchase order, receiving updates stock on hand automatically, and the entire chain is linked to the asset that triggered the need.

Unlike MP2 and comparable legacy CMMS tools, Tero.Ops eliminates the integration overhead and data silos that come from stitching together separate maintenance, inventory, and procurement systems.

### 4. Mobile-Native Field Operations vs Desktop-First UX

Tero.Ops is purpose-built for the field technician workflow. Every entity — assets, jobs, orders, inventory items, meters, projects — automatically receives a scannable QR code. A technician scans a code on physical equipment, is taken directly to that asset's detail page, accesses its maintenance history and linked spare parts, and creates a job record — all from a mobile device, without manual ID entry.

Unlike Fiix and other CMMS tools with responsive web interfaces adapted for mobile, Tero.Ops ships as native iOS and Android apps via Capacitor in addition to its PWA, built from the ground up on React 18, Ionic 8, and TypeScript.

